Consider a 3x3 matrix A which represents the supply, demand, and price values of three different goods in a global market. The elements of the matrix A are as follows:

A = [a1, a2, a3; a4, a5, a6; a7, a8, a9]

Given that the trace of the matrix (the sum of the diagonal elements) equals the total market value (TMV) of all goods, and the trace of the matrix squared (Tr(A^2)) equals the total potential market value (TPMV), find the values of a1, a5, a9 if:

TMV = 300;
TPMV = 10000;
The sum of all the elements in the matrix A equals to the total market supply (TMS) and TMS = 600;

Note: For simplicity, assume all the non-diagonal elements in the matrix A are equal to each other.
